## Themainsustainability risks and/uni00A0opportunities 3.2

In line withDirective 2014/95/EU on non-financial reporting as transposed into Frenchlaw (article/uni00A0R./uni00A0225-105 of the French Commercial Code), Pernod Ricard publishes a 'Non-Financial Statement'. This Statement requires the Group to publish its business model and information on key non-financial risks.These include risks related to the environment, employment, society,human rights, tax evasion (pursuant to Act no./uni00A02018-898 on combatting fraud) and corruption. For more information on Pernod Ricard's business model, please refer to Section/uni00A01 'Extracts from the integrated annual report' and for more information on the Group's key non-financial risks please see subsections/uni00A03.2.1 and 3.2.2 below.

## Presentation of the methodology 3.2.1

Pernod Ricard adopted the following methodology:

- every three years, the mainrisks faced by Pernod Ricard are glyph<c=1,font=/AAFOBE+ArialMT> mapped by direct affiliates and HQ functions and then consolidated at HQ level by the Group's Internal Audit Department. Updated in FY21, the/uni00A0Group's risk mapping presents and classifies the risks according to their potential impact and occurrence across the Group's activities. Some of these risks are specific to sustainability issues. The/uni00A0Group's major risks and the process for identifying them are discussed in section/uni00A04 of this document;
- the same Group'srisk mapping methodology and tool is used glyph<c=1,font=/AAFOBE+ArialMT> to identify the main sustainability risks for the 'Non-Financial Statement';
- led by the Sustainability & Responsibility Department, these glyph<c=1,font=/AAFOBE+ArialMT> sustainability risks are subject to in-depth analysis through research, competitive benchmarking and internal and external stakeholder dialogue (see subsection/uni00A03.1.1.2 'Addressing stakeholder expectations across the entire business, from grain to glass'); and the Group's materiality matrix last updated in 2020. Otherkey HQ experts including operations, legal, HR, public affairs and finance were also involved to confirm the top eight risks and opportunities;
- the identified sustainability risks and opportunities are then glyph<c=1,font=/AAFOBE+ArialMT> cross-referenced with the 2021 Group Risk Mapping to confirm and ensure consistency with the Group'smajor risks in Section/uni00A04;
- the resulting eight non-financial risksand opportunities were glyph<c=1,font=/AAFOBE+ArialMT> subsequently presented to and signed off by the S&R Senior Steering Committee and the S&R Committee of the Board of Directors.

## Theeight risks and opportunities identified 3.2.2

The definitions of the eight main risks and opportunities can be found in the table below. Targets, policies, due diligence procedures, and key performance indicators are presented in detail in subsections/uni00A03.3 'The/uni00A0four pillars of the Good Times from a Good Place Roadmap' and 3.4 'Ethics and compliance'. In the interest of transparency, other/uni00A0indicators have been presented alongside the policies applied, depending on the issues addressed.

Given the nature of our activities, we consider that the 'tax evasion' referred to in article/uni00A0L./uni00A0225-102-1 of French Commercial Code does not constitute a major non-financial risk for the Group. It was therefore not felt necessary to explore it in this 'Non-Financial Statement'. Nevertheless, 'tax evasion' is discussed in subsection/uni00A03.4.1.4 'Tax/uni00A0policy'.

